WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.040
Thanks a lot for having me here, I'm very happy to talk to you about an infrastructure

00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:18.360
that we have just set up at Covestro and in my presentation I wanted to show you a little

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:25.240
bit of what we did and what is a good practice from our perspective if you want to integrate

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:30.100
professional posit products into your infrastructure.

00:00:30.100 --> 00:00:38.160
Just before we start let me give you the opportunity to introduce me quickly.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:44.320
So I belong to a company called Eora, we were founded in 2010 and we do data science from

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:45.959
the very beginning on.

00:00:45.959 --> 00:00:49.880
We are about 50 employees at the moment and we are located in Germany, pretty much in

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:56.040
the center of Germany, not too far away from the geographical center of the EU and we

00:00:56.040 --> 00:01:02.400
are a posit partner since 2017 and our mission is empowering data-driven intelligence and

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:07.519
that is pretty much in line, I think, what the mission of posit is.

00:01:07.519 --> 00:01:14.919
So we have four pillars of what we do, so we have consulting services, use case workshops,

00:01:14.919 --> 00:01:20.800
proof of concept projects and implementation of algorithms into productive environments,

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:25.559
we have trainings, we have infrastructure and we have data science software.

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:30.800
Today I will focus on the pillar of data science infrastructure, this is what we call when

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:37.919
we kind of help companies that have an internal large group of data scientists which want

00:01:37.919 --> 00:01:41.279
to use professional products.

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:46.599
And yeah, as the situation is a little bit complicated I also want to introduce our customer,

00:01:46.599 --> 00:01:52.239
it's a company called Covestro which is also located in Germany.

00:01:52.239 --> 00:01:57.120
It's quite big, 80,000 employees, 50 production sites all around the globe and the headquarter

00:01:57.120 --> 00:02:06.440
in Germany and what they do is they create polymers and high sophisticated and high performance

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:11.360
plastic components that you will use in everyday life.

00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:17.639
So probably almost everybody of you have used some sort of product from Covestro.

00:02:17.639 --> 00:02:24.279
And the situation where we have started was that there was already an existing data science

00:02:24.279 --> 00:02:29.919
team, so Covestro does data science since, I don't know, 100 years or so because they

00:02:29.919 --> 00:02:33.080
do chemical trials and experiments and stuff like that.

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:41.000
So they are kind of a data science centric company from the very beginning on.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:47.440
And they just wanted to bring their infrastructure and their way of how to do data science on

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:49.119
the next level.

00:02:49.119 --> 00:02:53.800
So this is how we came in and I think this is important because the situation is probably

00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:59.720
a bit different if data science is more or less newly introduced to a company or if there's

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:07.160
already an existing team that does something and wants to mature to the next level.

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:15.119
So the general challenge when it comes to building up a centralized data science infrastructure,

00:03:15.119 --> 00:03:22.000
we heard this also in the keynote speeches, is that there are two perspectives on how

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:25.559
it feels like to be a captain of your ship.

00:03:25.559 --> 00:03:30.000
So the IT operation perspective is pretty much like that.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.279
So you have a pretty big ship.

00:03:32.279 --> 00:03:36.720
You want to drive it over the Atlantic Ocean, for example.

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:40.199
Once the course is set, you don't want to make any changes anymore.

00:03:40.199 --> 00:03:43.600
And if nothing happens, then you had a good day because you were good.

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:51.080
Well, I know it's a little bit over the top, but to make the point a little bit clearer.

00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:56.320
As a data scientist, it feels a little bit more like this, to be captain of your ship.

00:03:56.320 --> 00:04:01.119
You want to have a powerful motor.

00:04:01.119 --> 00:04:04.839
You want to be able to change your direction quickly.

00:04:04.839 --> 00:04:09.320
And in most cases, you are not so far away from the shoreline.

00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:13.839
You typically wouldn't cross the ocean with such a boat.

00:04:13.839 --> 00:04:15.720
But this is kind of the way it works.

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:21.040
And there are also other perspectives, business perspectives or data governance perspectives,

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:24.760
which are pretty much somewhere in the middle of these.

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:30.200
And so one of the key challenges, from my perspective, is to bring those two perspectives

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:31.200
together.

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:32.839
It's not either with this or that.

00:04:32.839 --> 00:04:37.519
Both perspectives are valid.

00:04:37.519 --> 00:04:44.040
So those implementation projects are typically successful if both sides have a mutual understanding

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:47.399
of the other side.

00:04:47.399 --> 00:04:53.000
And this is, generally speaking, not particular for Covestro, I would say.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:56.480
Well, at Covestro, we did it in a three-step way.

00:04:56.480 --> 00:05:02.260
This is actually our good practice of how to introduce centralized data science infrastructures.

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:11.279
So the first step is an assessment step, where we try to find out, okay, where are you?

00:05:11.279 --> 00:05:12.600
What's your position at the moment?

00:05:12.660 --> 00:05:16.559
So what are the databases that you could never get rid of, for example?

00:05:16.559 --> 00:05:23.359
And what are the technologies where you say, well, they are not up-to-date anymore.

00:05:23.359 --> 00:05:27.040
And it might be possible to migrate.

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:31.279
And we also want to know, where are you now in terms of data science use cases?

00:05:31.279 --> 00:05:39.799
And where are you seeing yourself in the foreseeable future, in the next two, three years or so?

00:05:39.799 --> 00:05:45.600
And yeah, one of the central aspects of those assessments is to bring all the perspectives,

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:50.000
the business perspective, the data governance perspective, the IT operation perspective,

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.799
and the data science perspective all together.

00:05:53.799 --> 00:05:59.519
And this is really important to have from every stakeholder group, somebody on the table

00:05:59.519 --> 00:06:01.320
all at once, right?

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:06.279
So that there's a common understanding where we want to go and how to do it.

00:06:06.279 --> 00:06:08.399
The next step is the implementation itself.

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:13.920
It means just setting up the infrastructure where we have just decided for.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:19.880
And it's, yeah, the implementation step, from our point of view, is really like you would

00:06:19.880 --> 00:06:21.799
do it in a data science project.

00:06:21.799 --> 00:06:23.359
You think of iterations.

00:06:23.359 --> 00:06:30.119
You start with a minimal viable product where somebody can use it and where you can gain

00:06:30.119 --> 00:06:37.119
the experiences from the users, from the data scientists, in order to improve the infrastructure.

00:06:37.119 --> 00:06:39.600
And finally, there's the operation side.

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:45.079
So once everything is in place and the business and data science people are kind of running

00:06:45.079 --> 00:06:49.799
crucial apps on this infrastructure, it needs to be operated.

00:06:49.799 --> 00:06:52.760
And then there's like a step forward, step back.

00:06:52.760 --> 00:07:00.359
It's like DevOps idea, implement and operate more or less at the same time.

00:07:00.359 --> 00:07:06.079
So after we finished the assessment with Covestro, we had like a list of challenges

00:07:06.079 --> 00:07:12.640
that they faced with their existing infrastructure or with the existing way of how they do data

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:13.640
science.

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:18.519
And we had a list of goals where they wanted to go.

00:07:18.519 --> 00:07:24.200
So the challenges were like there were 20 to 30 Python developers.

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:26.519
Well, that's not the challenge in itself.

00:07:26.519 --> 00:07:34.559
But they were distributed across multiple locations and multiple business lines.

00:07:34.559 --> 00:07:39.920
So there was actually something like an internal meetup of the data scientists who like exchange

00:07:39.920 --> 00:07:41.359
what they do.

00:07:41.359 --> 00:07:45.440
But it was not really the case that they feel like a common group.

00:07:45.440 --> 00:07:50.399
They were more or less splitted in their departments.

00:07:50.399 --> 00:07:54.920
The data science infrastructure itself was pretty much decentralized.

00:07:54.920 --> 00:08:02.440
So while they had some kind of advanced workflows, but basically everybody was working on his

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:04.920
or her laptop.

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:08.239
So this was kind of the original situation.

00:08:08.239 --> 00:08:12.399
And they expected a substantial growth in data.

00:08:12.399 --> 00:08:17.320
And I guess this is what every organization can say, that there is a substantial growth

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:20.559
in data.

00:08:20.559 --> 00:08:28.519
On the IT operation side, that was quite high administrative overhead to set up all those

00:08:28.519 --> 00:08:32.119
images of R and all the packages.

00:08:32.119 --> 00:08:38.359
And it was also not so easy to tackle the compliance issues that you have in a larger

00:08:38.359 --> 00:08:39.359
organization.

00:08:39.359 --> 00:08:43.479
They managed to do it, but it just took a bit too much time to do it.

00:08:43.479 --> 00:08:49.479
And they were looking for something which makes it easier for them.

00:08:49.479 --> 00:08:56.159
And of course, like always, if you work in a decentralized infrastructure, they had issues

00:08:56.159 --> 00:09:04.520
with compatibility, version dependencies, and all those things which you might all know.

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:12.039
And this is one aspect of a centralized infrastructure that you can really get rid of this stuff.

00:09:12.039 --> 00:09:15.880
These are the challenges, the main challenges they face.

00:09:16.359 --> 00:09:20.000
On the other hand, we have goals.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.919
So what do they want?

00:09:21.919 --> 00:09:24.599
They want to be able to collaborate.

00:09:24.599 --> 00:09:28.640
They want to be able to share projects and results.

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:34.799
They want to have a central package management so that it's easy to exchange the packages

00:09:34.799 --> 00:09:42.359
and to get always the same version that all the others have.

00:09:42.359 --> 00:09:49.679
They were looking for efficiency, so they want to reduce the efforts of the admin people.

00:09:49.679 --> 00:09:51.400
And they want a consistent data governance.

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:54.559
I'm not talking too much about the governance issue, but this is also important.

00:09:54.559 --> 00:09:58.640
Not only the infrastructure, also the data governance is important.

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:03.239
And this was on their list of goals.

00:10:03.239 --> 00:10:09.080
Because of the growth they were expecting and all the new technology that's coming up

00:10:09.119 --> 00:10:15.159
all the time, they wanted to be able to scale out horizontally and vertically.

00:10:15.159 --> 00:10:20.640
But they still wanted to have everything secure, of course.

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:24.760
And they wanted easy development pipelines, so it is easy to develop something and to

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:29.919
bring it to the business user as easy as possible.

00:10:29.919 --> 00:10:37.280
What we did then is we set up an infrastructure which is posit-centric infrastructure, if

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:38.280
you will.

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:43.799
And in the next couple of slides, well, it's actually just one slide, I will show you how

00:10:43.799 --> 00:10:48.280
this infrastructure looked like a little bit more into detail.

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:53.159
Not all the details, but I hope you can get an idea of what it looked like and it might

00:10:53.159 --> 00:10:57.280
help you to do the same in your organization.

00:10:57.280 --> 00:11:03.559
So first of all, we have set up a posit workbench on AWS.

00:11:03.559 --> 00:11:07.200
And this is what the developers were using from the beginning on.

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:12.520
And the cool thing is if you switch from laptop to a centralized posit workbench on

00:11:12.520 --> 00:11:17.679
AWS, it's not much different from the user's experience.

00:11:17.679 --> 00:11:20.799
And that's really, really important for the acceptance.

00:11:20.799 --> 00:11:28.880
So there's especially one user who is kind of, I don't know, he works with R for 25 years

00:11:28.880 --> 00:11:29.880
or so.

00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:31.880
He's really good, really, really good.

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:34.520
And he was like, OK, I have to have everything on my laptop.

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:36.200
This is the only way it will work for me.

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:41.260
So I cannot believe that it's possible if we have an infrastructure on the cloud.

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:45.640
And finally, after we finished everything, he would not want to work every time in this

00:11:45.640 --> 00:11:47.599
life again on his laptop.

00:11:47.599 --> 00:11:52.559
So that was our greatest success indicator, actually.

00:11:52.559 --> 00:11:59.840
Yeah, so then we kind of combined the workbench with an Azure Active Directory and we used

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:06.599
SAML to do the communication between Puzzle and the Active Directory.

00:12:06.599 --> 00:12:11.359
And the interesting thing here is, and we see this in many organizations, actually,

00:12:11.359 --> 00:12:14.640
they mix the cloud providers.

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:20.679
So the operation platform is AWS, but the platform that provided the Active Directory

00:12:20.679 --> 00:12:26.159
is Azure in this case.

00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:32.000
And when we started the implementation, we actually had sessions that worked on the server,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:37.400
but it was clear from the beginning on that we're going to switch to a Kubernetes setup

00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:42.599
where the sessions are kind of spawned into a Kubernetes cluster.

00:12:42.599 --> 00:12:46.440
And the way we did it here is like an off-host execution.

00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:50.919
That means that the Puzzle Workbench server is not in Kubernetes.

00:12:50.919 --> 00:12:53.400
Only the sessions are running in Kubernetes.

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:55.559
And that worked out pretty well.

00:12:55.559 --> 00:13:00.200
And we distinguished between kind of three load groups.

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:04.719
We had a low, medium, and high load.

00:13:04.719 --> 00:13:09.799
That means of the computational power that the applications or the computation needs.

00:13:09.799 --> 00:13:19.119
And that was really useful in order to provide the respective resources to the users.

00:13:19.119 --> 00:13:22.559
And additionally, we had an NFS share.

00:13:22.559 --> 00:13:28.440
So that's an external file share where the users had their home directories on.

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:34.359
And that is also a good practice from our perspective to have this on a separated server.

00:13:34.359 --> 00:13:39.039
Whenever there's an issue on the Puzzle server, on the Workbench server, then you have the

00:13:39.039 --> 00:13:46.679
separated and you can just, you have no issues in updating, I think.

00:13:47.679 --> 00:13:55.679
Next step was to set up Puzzle Connect in a dev environment, development environment.

00:13:55.679 --> 00:13:57.880
This is how we started.

00:13:57.880 --> 00:14:04.640
And the developer were able to push what they have done as APIs or Shiny apps or reports

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:06.479
to this Connect server.

00:14:06.479 --> 00:14:09.039
And they were also consumers of this Connect server.

00:14:09.039 --> 00:14:14.479
So it's not only that they kind of provided stuff to the business people, but it's also

00:14:14.479 --> 00:14:19.280
the case that they used it themselves and it made their life much easier to have a central,

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:26.400
reliable base where the data and the analytics are kind of to be found.

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:32.159
And it's easy to be sure that everything is in one place.

00:14:32.159 --> 00:14:39.039
So the developers actually are heavy users of the Connect server themselves.

00:14:39.039 --> 00:14:46.119
Same idea is we kind of externalized the app directories on an NFS share.

00:14:46.119 --> 00:14:52.799
And there's probably a detail, but very helpful, there's a Postgres DB within Connect and we

00:14:52.799 --> 00:14:55.159
kind of externalized this too.

00:14:55.159 --> 00:14:56.280
This has two advantages.

00:14:56.280 --> 00:15:00.840
The first is you can do updates on the Connect server while it's running.

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:05.559
And whenever you have to set up your Connect server again, everything is kind of on a separate

00:15:05.559 --> 00:15:06.559
server.

00:15:07.080 --> 00:15:09.320
That worked out pretty well.

00:15:09.320 --> 00:15:13.840
And then the same thing with the production environment.

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:17.799
So it's basically two types of server.

00:15:17.799 --> 00:15:20.320
So it's a two-tier environment, if you will.

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:23.440
So development plus test.

00:15:23.440 --> 00:15:29.679
And the production environment, and now for other customers, we have a three-tier where

00:15:29.679 --> 00:15:32.039
we kind of distinguish between development and test.

00:15:32.039 --> 00:15:36.520
So in this case, it was OK to just go with one development server.

00:15:36.520 --> 00:15:44.159
And the production environment, and where the business users, you know, on the other

00:15:44.159 --> 00:15:51.799
end of the diagram, in the infrastructure perspective at least, they are heavily using

00:15:51.799 --> 00:15:58.919
the APIs, mainly the shiny apps that were provided from the developers.

00:15:58.919 --> 00:15:59.919
So that's kind of cool.

00:15:59.919 --> 00:16:08.039
And finally, we added the package manager on top of that as an external thing, and also

00:16:08.039 --> 00:16:14.440
externalized the packages themselves and the metadata of those packages.

00:16:14.440 --> 00:16:18.559
So this is more or less the infrastructure, how it looks like.

00:16:18.559 --> 00:16:20.039
There are some components missing.

00:16:20.039 --> 00:16:21.039
There was also Git.

00:16:21.039 --> 00:16:22.679
There was also continuous integration.

00:16:22.679 --> 00:16:24.359
It's not everything on the table.

00:16:24.359 --> 00:16:28.679
And there are also other perspectives which are quite important.

00:16:28.679 --> 00:16:33.280
When you introduce something like this, and this is, for example, like how the data flows,

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:39.080
the data governance perspective, I was not talking about that, and also the use case

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:40.080
perspective.

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:41.919
So how do you manage use cases?

00:16:41.919 --> 00:16:45.559
So if a business user comes up and say, OK, I have this and that use case, and that would

00:16:45.559 --> 00:16:52.359
be pretty cool if I have this, somebody has to evaluate what is important and prioritize

00:16:52.359 --> 00:16:54.880
what is important, what's not important.

00:16:54.880 --> 00:16:59.000
Because it will not take long until you have so many demand from the business users that

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.280
you are not able to serve everything.

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:06.000
And this is another perspective that I have not here on this slide.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:13.079
Yeah, so to summarize what I just said, what were the advantages?

00:17:13.079 --> 00:17:19.959
So it is easy to collaborate for the data scientists across departments, also to communicate

00:17:19.959 --> 00:17:23.239
between data scientists and business users.

00:17:23.239 --> 00:17:30.319
So the agility of data science was also introduced into other parts of the organization, just

00:17:30.319 --> 00:17:34.800
what we heard in the keynote speech before.

00:17:34.800 --> 00:17:36.040
That's an interesting aspect.

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:40.880
If data science agility mindset goes into the organization, that is good for the organization

00:17:40.880 --> 00:17:42.479
as well.

00:17:42.479 --> 00:17:47.280
The maintainability was improved, and that was good from the perspective of the IT operators.

00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:52.680
So they were really happy, so that it is much easier for them to manage everything.

00:17:52.680 --> 00:17:59.079
The performance was increased, and it was much more flexible.

00:17:59.079 --> 00:18:04.119
One thing I forgot to mention, I know, I'm sorry, I will mention later.

00:18:04.119 --> 00:18:08.079
So okay, just forget about it.

00:18:08.079 --> 00:18:13.199
And it was, another advantage is that it is in line with compliance guidelines.

00:18:13.199 --> 00:18:19.000
I mean, they were before, of course, in line with compliance guidelines.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:25.520
But this infrastructure is also compliant, and that is, of course, a very important aspect.

00:18:25.520 --> 00:18:30.439
So what I wanted to say a minute ago was avoid manual steps from the beginning on.

00:18:30.439 --> 00:18:35.959
Something that I haven't mentioned yet, we did this from the very beginning on with infrastructure

00:18:35.959 --> 00:18:38.560
as code and Terraform in this example.

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:43.400
And that's pretty cool, because if you want to roll out the same environment in the Asian

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:47.160
Pacific region, for example, it's just one click.

00:18:47.160 --> 00:18:48.520
Very easy.

00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:52.439
And we have other use cases, for example, where we kind of set up a training environment

00:18:52.439 --> 00:18:54.280
just for a couple of days.

00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:57.319
And if you do it in Terraform, this is really easy to do.

00:18:57.319 --> 00:19:03.880
So this is really our kind of learning there, that we always build infrastructure with Terraform

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:07.439
or similar tools.

00:19:07.439 --> 00:19:14.599
So the question of cloud versus on-prem versus hybrid infrastructure, that is at least in

00:19:14.599 --> 00:19:15.959
Germany very virulent.

00:19:15.959 --> 00:19:20.359
So many companies still not kind of completely going into the cloud.

00:19:20.359 --> 00:19:25.439
Everything I've just showed, although it was created in the cloud, it's possible to do

00:19:25.439 --> 00:19:29.479
this on-prem as well, and also with the Kubernetes cluster.

00:19:29.479 --> 00:19:31.560
You can run the Kubernetes cluster on-prem.

00:19:31.560 --> 00:19:35.800
I don't know if I would want to do it, but it's possible.

00:19:35.800 --> 00:19:40.040
So it's always good to develop the infrastructure in close coordination with data science, also

00:19:40.040 --> 00:19:41.719
with the business users.

00:19:41.719 --> 00:19:44.280
That is our kind of lessons learned.

00:19:44.280 --> 00:19:47.199
And the implementation in iterations really makes sense.

00:19:47.199 --> 00:19:49.239
So don't do everything at once.

00:19:49.239 --> 00:19:51.079
What's your lookout?

00:19:51.079 --> 00:19:53.239
What is your minimal viable product?

00:19:53.239 --> 00:19:57.079
Implement this and have it used, and then you get feedback by the users.

00:19:57.079 --> 00:20:02.520
All right, yeah, and that's everything I'd have to say.

00:20:02.520 --> 00:20:04.280
Thank you for your attention.

00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:09.680
You find my contact details here, so if you are interested to chat about some more details,

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:11.319
I'm happy to talk with you.

